  "prompt": "Can you be allergic to meat and fish?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to be allergic to meat and fish. Allergies to these foods are relatively less common than allergies to other foods like nuts, dairy, or shellfish, but they can occur.\n\n1. **Fish Allergies:** Fish allergies are one of the more common food allergies and can occur with a wide range of fish species. Symptoms can include hives, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and in severe cases, anaphylaxis.\n\n2. **Meat Allergies:** There are also reported cases of allergies to mammalian meats (beef, pork, lamb) and poultry (chicken, turkey). One well-documented condition is alpha-gal syndrome, which is associated with allergic reactions to red meat and is linked to tick bites, particularly from the Lone Star tick.\n\nIf someone suspects they have a meat or fish allergy, it is important to consult with a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and management, which may involve allergy testing and creating an appropriate avoidance strategy.",
